║                                                                           Docker Installation                                                                           ║
╚═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

   Installing Docker
   ─────────────────
      1. Open a terminal window
      2. Login as the superuser (root on CentOS/RHEL)
      3. Remove any existing docker components by typing the following command(s) into the terminal window:

            yum remove docker docker-common docker-selinux docker-engine

      4. Install the required docker components by typing the following command(s) into the terminal window:

            yum --noplugins --enablerepo "*" --disablerepo "*media*" install yum-utils device-mapper-persistent-data lvm2

      5. Modify the yum configuration file, /etc/yum.conf, to suppress the checking of SSL certificates by adding the following line

            sslverify=False

      6. Add the docker repository by typing the following command(s) into the terminal window:

            yum-config-manager --add-repo https://download.docker.com/linux/centos/docker-ce.repo

      7. Add docker by typing the following command(s) into the terminal window:

            yum --noplugins --enablerepo "*" --disablerepo "*media*" install docker-ce

      8. Start the docker service by typing the following command(s) into the terminal window:

            systemctl start docker

      9. Create a directory to hold the certificates by typing the following command(s) into the terminal window:

            mkdir /root/security

     10. Change to the new directory by typing the following command(s) into the terminal window:

            cd /root/security

     11. Copy the certificate tools by typing the following command(s) into the terminal window:

            scp root@<machine-ip-address>:/<source-path>/Certificate-and-tools.tar.gz .

     12. Expand the archive by typing the following command(s) into the terminal window:

            tar -xzvf Certificate-and-tools.tar.gz

     13. Install the necessary certficates by typing the following command(s) into the terminal window:

            ./AddCertsToAnchor.sh

     14. Add the docker group (may already be added during installation) by typing the following command(s) into the terminal window:

            groupadd docker

     15. Add your username to the docker group by typing the following command(s) into the terminal window:

            usermod -aG docker $USER

     16. Logout and login so your group membership is re-evaluated



